		<p>
			Just like for exponents (and exponential functions) we had a list of rules, we also have commonly-used algebraic rules for manipulating logarithm functions. These work whether or not we consider the logarithm to be base-<m>e</m> or base-<m>10</m>, or any other base. Since we will most often use the natural logarithm, <m>\ln(x)</m>, we will write the rules that way. The following rules work for real numbers <m>a, b, n</m>.
