	<li><p><m>\ln(1) =</m></p></li>
	<li><p><m>\ln(e) =</m></p></li>

		</ul></p>

		<p>
			Common applications of exponentials involve solving equations that arise in chemistry, microbiology, or population growth. Suppose the function <m>p(t) = 36.2e^{0.012t}</m> describes the population of some organism as a function of time measured in weeks.
		</p>

		<p><ul>	<li><p>What is the initial population size?</p></li>
	<li><p>What is the population size after six weeks?</p></li>
	<li><p>When has the population reached twice its initial population size?</p></li>

		</ul></p>

		<p>
			Suppose that the amount of radioactivity that remains from an injected medical tracer is described by <m>r(t) = 15e^{-0.027t}</m>, where <m>t</m> is in hours.
		</p>

		<p><ul>	<li><p>What is the initial amount of radioactivity?</p></li>
	<li><p>How much radioactivity remains when it has reached half of the initial amount?</p></li>
	<li><p>When has the radioactivity reached half its initial amount?</p></li>

		</ul></p>

		<p>
			An important application of logarithms, related to graphing, was hinted at in the table a few pages back. The data from the ordered pairs are just a few <q>nice</q> points from the graph of <m>f(x) = \sqrt{x}</m>. That doesn’t seem like it has much to do with anything, but remember we can write <m>y = f(x) = x^{\frac{1}{2}}</m>. Let’s take logarithms of both sides and see what happens. <em>As long as we’re careful</em>, it doesn’t really matter which logarithm we use, but we will use the base-10 logarithm for consistency with our earlier example.
		</p>

		<p>
			Historically (and still even today) scientists have been obsessed with graphing straight lines.
		</p>


